<org.eclipse.epf.uma:ContentDescription xmi:version="2.0" xmlns:xmi="http://www.omg.org/XMI" xmlns:org.eclipse.epf.uma="http://www.eclipse.org/epf/uma/1.0.6/uma.ecore" xmlns:epf="http://www.eclipse.org/epf" epf:version="1.5.1" xmlns:rmc="http://www.ibm.com/rmc" rmc:version="7.5.1" xmi:id="-ekvCE3E5AIhPqDGPD44VsA" name="uam_logical_pers,_aiIn4Ou6Edytvcf-4U2D3Q" guid="-ekvCE3E5AIhPqDGPD44VsA" authors="DW Enstrom" changeDate="2015-02-19T18:00:44.316-0500" changeDescription="new" version="1.0.0">
  <mainDescription>&lt;a id=&quot;XE_Logical_Perspective__guidance&quot; name=&quot;XE_Logical_Perspective__guidance&quot;>&lt;/a> &#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Introduction&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The Logical Perspective defines the logical level view of the system.&amp;nbsp; The various models defined show&amp;nbsp;how&#xD;
    people interact with processes at various locations within the system, and the things they handle and use (logical&#xD;
    entities). The models also show how these different aspects and things must relate to one another, both statically and&#xD;
    dynamically, to produce the&amp;nbsp;desired business results. It places emphasis on the structure of entities, roles, the&#xD;
    business locations and processes, and their active responsibilities and interactions. The models show all aspects&#xD;
    needed to support business activities and processes and related entities to obtain the desired results for the various&#xD;
    actors. Computational aspects, such as &lt;em>storage&lt;/em> and &lt;em>server&lt;/em> and &lt;em>database&lt;/em> are added to this&#xD;
    logical level model.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;img alt=&quot;Logical Perspective&quot; src=&quot;./resources/pers_log.png&quot; />&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The key elements of the&amp;nbsp;Logical Perspective, summarized in the figure above,&amp;nbsp;are:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../../UAM/workproducts/uam_logical_entity_24D5BB51.html&quot;&#xD;
        guid=&quot;_e5AooNjOEdyPdoI9d5Dn-Q&quot;>Logical Entity&lt;/a>&amp;nbsp;represents deliverables, resources, and significant pieces&#xD;
        of information that are used or produced by activities and tasks and are captured in a &lt;a&#xD;
        class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot; href=&quot;./../../../UAM/workproducts/uam_logical_entity_model_2ACBC73E.html&quot;&#xD;
        guid=&quot;_UkGJEM6jEdymj4NXv8-FYA&quot;>Artifact: Logical Entity Model&lt;/a>.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithUserText&quot; href=&quot;./../../../UAM/workproducts/uam_logical_activity_C51C2E7.html&quot;&#xD;
        guid=&quot;_Q4X6ENi7EdyPdoI9d5Dn-Q&quot;>Logical Activities&lt;/a>&amp;nbsp;show how the processes/tasks,&amp;nbsp;logical roles and&#xD;
        logical entities (and optionally business events and rules) work together to perform a business activity.&#xD;
        Activities, processes, events and rules are all captured in the &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
        href=&quot;./../../../UAM/workproducts/uam_logical_process_model_FEBA9C7C.html&quot; guid=&quot;_MMYawM6kEdymj4NXv8-FYA&quot;>Artifact:&#xD;
        Logical Process Model&lt;/a>. &#xD;
        &lt;ul>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../../UAM/guidances/guidelines/uam_logical_event_BB7E7B95.html&quot;&#xD;
                guid=&quot;_ANn24AYSEeSyDIZvZjuaLg&quot;>Logical Event&lt;/a>s represent important occurrences in the daily operation of&#xD;
                the business that potentially trigger business processes.&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../../UAM/guidances/guidelines/uam_logical_rule_5CF4767E.html&quot;&#xD;
                guid=&quot;_KM8p8AYWEeSyDIZvZjuaLg&quot;>Logical Rule&lt;/a>s are declarations of policies or conditions that must be&#xD;
                satisfied during the execution of business processes.&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
        &lt;/ul>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../../UAM/workproducts/uam_logical_location_AD182F9A.html&quot;&#xD;
        guid=&quot;_EI51cNjJEdyPdoI9d5Dn-Q&quot;>Logical Location&lt;/a>s&amp;nbsp;partition the model into interdependent areas of&#xD;
        responsibilities based upon a logical view of the system, captured in the &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
        href=&quot;./../../../UAM/workproducts/uam_logical_locations_model_38F9B7F3.html&quot;&#xD;
        guid=&quot;_2x718M6kEdymj4NXv8-FYA&quot;>Artifact: Logical Locations Model&lt;/a>. They encapsulate their resources, and provide&#xD;
        services through well-defined interfaces, to other parts of the business.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../../UAM/workproducts/uam_logical_role_58F85B4C.html&quot;&#xD;
        guid=&quot;_mOE5ENjLEdyPdoI9d5Dn-Q&quot;>Logical Role&lt;/a>s interact with activities and processes—they represent the&#xD;
        interface to the system for users (or perhaps automated systems).&amp;nbsp;In the Logical Perspective they represent an&#xD;
        abstraction of a human or software, or even a system containing humans, hardware and software (which are not&#xD;
        decomposed further).&amp;nbsp;Actors aggregate roles in order to perform a particular function with the system (e.g.,&#xD;
        order a product). This is all captured in the &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
        href=&quot;./../../../UAM/workproducts/uam_logical_roles_model_DA24EFC0.html&quot; guid=&quot;_b-QioM6lEdymj4NXv8-FYA&quot;>Artifact:&#xD;
        Logical Roles Model&lt;/a>.&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The Logical Perspective is documented with a number of possible diagrams, see &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../../UAM/guidances/guidelines/uam_diagrams_in_logical_pers_FA9238A.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;_PxJUAOoZEdytvcf-4U2D3Q&quot;>Guideline: Logical Perspective Views&lt;/a>. Each Perspective, and viewpoint within, has a&#xD;
    modeling language defined, integrated into the Perspective Viewpoint Language, see: &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../../UAM/guidances/supportingmaterials/uam_lpl_simple_AB1449E6.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;_uOZlsEWJEeOfR_FtRm9PUg&quot;>Supporting Material: LPL Summary&lt;/a>&amp;nbsp;and &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../../UAM/guidances/supportingmaterials/uam_lpl_E063ECCA.html&quot; guid=&quot;_eNHwsLhwEeSeNe6SxZNlbg&quot;>Supporting&#xD;
    Material: LPL Defined&lt;/a>.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The following are some characteristics of the Logical Perspective:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        It articulates, using logical concepts and constructs and language,&amp;nbsp;a model that supports the view of the&#xD;
        system defined in the Business Perspective . It is a translation of this model from the business language and&#xD;
        concepts, to a logical level view of the computational solution that supports it.&amp;nbsp;The Logical Perspective is a&#xD;
        representation for technical managers and other technical people, using formal constructs and computational&#xD;
        aspects, of the area of business of interest.&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        It explores the essence of the system in a way that provides a bridge between the&amp;nbsp;business view (in the&#xD;
        Business Perspective)&amp;nbsp;to the&amp;nbsp;technology solutions as defined in the Technology Perspective.&amp;nbsp;Model&#xD;
        concepts and constructs&amp;nbsp;provide the formalisms necessary for architects to create this view, but in a way that&#xD;
        maintains linkage back to the business structures, concepts and requirements defined in the Business&#xD;
        Perspective.&amp;nbsp;This linkage is also maintained down to the Technology level.&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        It defines logical level solutions to the business concepts and requirements defined at the Business level—the&#xD;
        information technology solutions supporting the Business level are agreed. The implications of business activities,&#xD;
        strategies, plans and goals on the&amp;nbsp;IT architecture are identified, defined, documented and logical level&#xD;
        solutions are modeled.&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        A very important aspect of doing IT architecture is agreeing definitions,&amp;nbsp;the names for the objects and&#xD;
        relationships between objects. This permits system knowledge to be represented in a precise manner that can be&#xD;
        understood and validated by subject matter experts, but in a way that is useful to architects, managers and&#xD;
        implementers. See: &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
        href=&quot;./../../../UAM/guidances/practices/uam_glossary_7C5D47E2.html&quot; guid=&quot;_P6kB4NEDEdyC2cfK_t2EKQ&quot;>Practice:&#xD;
        Define a Robust Glossary&lt;/a> .&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;blockquote style=&quot;MARGIN-RIGHT: 0px&quot; dir=&quot;ltr&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;p>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>&lt;u>Note&lt;/u>:&lt;/strong> Since the Unified Architecture Method may model&amp;nbsp;the complete enterprise (or&#xD;
        business domain), the level of detail to be included in this model is a judgment call of the architect, based upon:&#xD;
    &lt;/p>&#xD;
    &lt;div style=&quot;MARGIN-LEFT: 2em&quot;>&#xD;
        &lt;ul>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                The objective of the architecture effort;&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                The size of the enterprise or (business line);&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Time and resource constraints.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
        &lt;/ul>&#xD;
    &lt;/div>&#xD;
&lt;/blockquote>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    &lt;a id=&quot;XE_Logical_Activity__naming_guidelines&quot; name=&quot;XE_Logical_Activity__naming_guidelines&quot;>&lt;/a>&lt;a&#xD;
    id=&quot;XE_Logical_Location__naming_guidelines&quot; name=&quot;XE_Logical_Location__naming_guidelines&quot;>&lt;/a>&lt;a&#xD;
    id=&quot;XE_Logical_Role__naming_guidelines&quot; name=&quot;XE_Logical_Role__naming_guidelines&quot;>&lt;/a>&lt;a&#xD;
    id=&quot;XE_Logical_Entity__naming_guidelines&quot; name=&quot;XE_Logical_Entity__naming_guidelines&quot;>&lt;/a>&lt;a&#xD;
    id=&quot;How to Name Business Workers and Business Entities&quot;&#xD;
    name=&quot;How to Name Business Workers and Business Entities&quot;>Naming Conventions&lt;/a>&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    In general, Logical Entities, Logical Activities, Logical Locations, and Logical Roles should have short, descriptive&#xD;
    names that are unique and recognizable.&amp;nbsp;Multiple word names are acceptable for clarity, but multiple names for the&#xD;
    same thing (an entity, location, activity or role) is a &lt;em>major&lt;/em> problem—therefore, if there is some contention&#xD;
    regarding a name/definition, work through it until a single name and definition is agreed, or multiple (logically&#xD;
    separate) things are identified and defined.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Logical Entities are named&amp;nbsp;to reflect the information they represent.&amp;nbsp;They must be defined in the Glossary&#xD;
    (along with the activities, locations and roles), since there are always differences of opinion regarding definitions,&#xD;
    and relationships as well. The state, or other properties of a Logical Entity, should not be included in its name.&#xD;
    Logical Entity names should be singular nouns. See &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../../UAM/guidances/guidelines/uam_logical_entity_3CA201C3.html&quot; guid=&quot;_n7HSsOX9EdyjVoHXO3Mbfg&quot;>Guideline:&#xD;
    Logical Entity&lt;/a>&amp;nbsp;and&amp;nbsp;&lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../../UAM/guidances/guidelines/uam_logical_entity_model_B675AAE2.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;_-zp8sOV5EdyjVoHXO3Mbfg&quot;>Guideline: Logical Entity Model&lt;/a> for more information.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Logical Activities, at many IT architecture levels, encompass a number of processes and tasks—the names should reflect&#xD;
    these processes and tasks, &lt;em>Human Resources Self-service&lt;/em> for example. In the logical level model we are trying&#xD;
    to detail the fully analyzed view of activities, complete with all generalizations, specializations, re-use and other&#xD;
    structure and behavioural aspects.&amp;nbsp;Generally,&amp;nbsp;the active form of&amp;nbsp;a&amp;nbsp;verb is useful for names (such&#xD;
    as &lt;em>Shipping&lt;/em>, &lt;em>Invoicing&lt;/em>, or &lt;em>Selling&lt;/em>) as is a reference to the purpose of the Logical&#xD;
    Activity. See &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../../UAM/guidances/guidelines/uam_logical_activity_3A404127.html&quot; guid=&quot;_7IOQYOxWEdytvcf-4U2D3Q&quot;>Guideline:&#xD;
    Logical Activity&lt;/a>&amp;nbsp;and&amp;nbsp;&lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../../UAM/guidances/guidelines/uam_logical_process_model_38D5D114.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;_Cr8VIOyGEdykP9GoXvwZVg&quot;>Guideline: Logical Process Model&lt;/a> for more information.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Logical Locations are named&amp;nbsp;to reflect the generic&amp;nbsp;and logical location that they represent. Logical Location&#xD;
    names should be singular nouns, such as &lt;em>Headquarters&lt;/em>, &lt;em>Factory&lt;/em>, &lt;em>Warehouse&lt;/em>, &lt;em>ATM&lt;/em>, for&#xD;
    example. At the logical level, the location model provides details regarding the computational aspects of the&#xD;
    locations, such as servers and&amp;nbsp;storage, and more details regarding the activities supported at&amp;nbsp;each location.&#xD;
    See &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot; href=&quot;./../../../UAM/guidances/guidelines/uam_logical_location_CBA4BCC.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;_mIiNkOxaEdytvcf-4U2D3Q&quot;>Guideline: Logical Location&lt;/a>&amp;nbsp;and&amp;nbsp;&lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../../UAM/guidances/guidelines/uam_logical_locations_model_C5E9456.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;_Fb2ngOSwEdyYxtlRIMoTnw&quot;>Guideline: Logical Locations Model&lt;/a> for more information.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Logical Role names reflect the primary activities that they interact with or are responsible for. At the logical level&#xD;
    decisions are made regarding whether or not a role equates to a human or a system/application. It also focuses on the&#xD;
    structure of roles and related navigation maps, and optionally the &lt;em>roles&lt;/em> to &lt;em>users&lt;/em> mappings.&amp;nbsp;IT&#xD;
    security aspects of roles are also defined. The name should reflect&amp;nbsp;the role played by the actor with the&#xD;
    activity.&amp;nbsp;Logical Roles define the solution, in other words this is when it is decided if a role is human or is a&#xD;
    system/application.&amp;nbsp;Other details of the solution include the structure of roles, how they related to actual users&#xD;
    of the enterprise systems, and how the roles are used to support the IT security&amp;nbsp;requirements. See&amp;nbsp;&lt;a&#xD;
    class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot; href=&quot;./../../../UAM/guidances/guidelines/uam_logical_role_A100F4F1.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;_f5YuQOxbEdytvcf-4U2D3Q&quot;>Guideline: Logical Actors and Roles&lt;/a> and&amp;nbsp;&lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../../UAM/guidances/guidelines/uam_logical_roles_model_9E48402E.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;_JE2zEO63Edy8F4k6ANL48Q&quot;>Guideline: Logical Roles Model&lt;/a> for more information.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Logical (business) Events and Rules are very useful&amp;nbsp;when defining an IT architecture.&amp;nbsp;Events should be named&#xD;
    in a way that indicates the occurrence or state change that it represents, in other words they generally have an entity&#xD;
    part and an action part, for example &lt;em>Order&lt;/em>&lt;em>Arrival&lt;/em>. Do not describe the reaction to the event in the&#xD;
    name. The specification of the event is also&amp;nbsp;independent of its triggers. See &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../../UAM/guidances/guidelines/uam_logical_event_BB7E7B95.html&quot; guid=&quot;_ANn24AYSEeSyDIZvZjuaLg&quot;>Guideline:&#xD;
    Logical Event&lt;/a>&amp;nbsp;and&amp;nbsp;&lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../../UAM/guidances/guidelines/uam_logical_rule_5CF4767E.html&quot; guid=&quot;_KM8p8AYWEeSyDIZvZjuaLg&quot;>Guideline:&#xD;
    Logical Rule&lt;/a> for more information. At the logical level, more detail regarding the event or rule is added,&#xD;
    including structure (if useful), and perhaps the definition of specific logical entities to represent the events and&#xD;
    rules that participate in the defined processes. Rules are also more structured and implementable.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    &lt;a id=&quot;The System Model and Information Systems&quot; name=&quot;The System Model and Information Systems&quot;>The Logical&#xD;
    Perspective and Information Systems&lt;/a>&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    In the Logical Perspective, Logical Roles describe the interface to the system for actors, whereas Logical Entities&#xD;
    represent those things that are produced and consumed by the activities.&amp;nbsp;The Logical Perspective defines how these&#xD;
    activities and entities&amp;nbsp;need to interact to produce the desired results for the business (actor). An Actor may&#xD;
    represent an abstraction of an automated system, but at the logical level the decision needs to be made—is&#xD;
    this&amp;nbsp;Actor a person or a system. Associated Roles may then be identified and clearly defined.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The Business Perspective and Logical Perspective (and Technology Perspective) address the same problem&amp;nbsp;domain&#xD;
    (i.e. the &quot;system&quot;) at two different abstraction levels. Therefore, the different views within each Perspective need to&#xD;
    remain consistent. We now introduce computational modeling details and concepts (like &lt;em>storage&lt;/em>); however,&#xD;
    specific technology solutions (such as StorageTech or SUN) are not defined.&amp;nbsp;Technology choices, namely the&#xD;
    enterprise technology standards, are defined in the Enterprise Perspective, including how they are to be deployed and&#xD;
    used.&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Certain relationship heuristics between the Business Perspective and the Logical Perspective contexts may be useful, as&#xD;
    you look for automation opportunities—but knowledge of technology solutions is also needed. Specific technical&#xD;
    solutions may be examined in order to refine and define the logical view, with the decision on the specific technology&#xD;
    left until the Technology Perspective is defined.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Links, associations and attributes in the Business Perspective may suggest structures and possible automation in the&#xD;
    Logical Perspective:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        When the business activities are large, long-lived, or combine work from several independent areas (as is the case&#xD;
        for many enterprise architecture business activities) then the Logical Perspective view of the activity will likely&#xD;
        have many Logical Processes / Tasks&amp;nbsp;in its model.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The things the activities manipulate&amp;nbsp;are modeled as logical entities, which are their&amp;nbsp;representations in&#xD;
        the information systems.&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Events are often implemented as messages&amp;nbsp;between tasks in processes at the Logical Perspective level. These&#xD;
        messages are also defined as logical entities.&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Associations and aggregations between business entities often give rise to corresponding associations and&#xD;
        aggregations between entity classes in the Logical Entity Model.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The Logical Activities&amp;nbsp;that manipulate Logical Entity classes in the Logical Perspective are&#xD;
        represented&amp;nbsp;by Business Entities accessed by Business Activities in the Business Perspective.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        A&amp;nbsp;business actor that directly uses a business activity also becomes a logical actor of the&amp;nbsp;logical&#xD;
        activity&amp;nbsp;in the Logical Perspective.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    These relationships are&amp;nbsp;useful when identifying requirements for the logical systems that support the business&#xD;
    model of the system.&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    As you model manipulations of business entities by business roles, it is evident that many of the operations on the&#xD;
    business entities would be performed with the assistance of some tool—perhaps computer-based. This is now explicitly&#xD;
    modeled as an information system within the logical models. As mentioned above, notions of computing and technology&#xD;
    (technology solutions) do not belong in the business level models, but are now introduced in the logical models.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    &lt;b>&lt;a id=&quot;Information Systems as Logical Actors&quot; name=&quot;Information Systems as Logical Actors&quot;>Systems as Logical&#xD;
    Actors&lt;/a>&lt;/b>&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Sometimes the employees of one business contact the employees of another business through the use of an information&#xD;
    system in the first business, from the perspective of the modeled business (receiving the request), that information&#xD;
    system is an actor. The logical solution is usually an interface (i.e., system actor), or possibly a human actor. As&#xD;
    noted, these choices are made here in the Logical Perspective.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    &lt;a id=&quot;XE_Logical_Perspective__characteristics_of_a_good&quot;&#xD;
    name=&quot;XE_Logical_Perspective__characteristics_of_a_good&quot;>&lt;/a>&lt;a id=&quot;Characteristics of a Good System Model&quot;&#xD;
    name=&quot;Characteristics of a Good System Model&quot;>Characteristics of a Good Logical&amp;nbsp;Perspective&lt;/a>&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The logical events (and rules), logical roles, logical entities, logical activities and logical locations completely&#xD;
    describe&amp;nbsp;the system at the logical level. The Logical Perspective provides a&amp;nbsp;comprehensive picture of the&#xD;
    system at an appropriate level of abstraction; appropriate for the objective of the modeling and the size of the system&#xD;
    being modeled.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Transition to the Technical Perspective&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The Technical Perspective is the evolution of the Logical Perspective with choices (and associated rationale) for the&#xD;
    transformation/realization. Some refactoring, of Logical Entities, Activities, Locations and Processes may be done,&#xD;
    adding more detail (as needed by technological choices) to describe the system at the technical level. Specific&#xD;
    technology choices, along with adjustments required to the IT architecture, are made and documented.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
</org.eclipse.epf.uma:ContentDescription>
